Not all work performed by children should be classified as child labour. According to the International Labor Organization (ILO), child labour can be defined as work that deprives children of their childhood, their potential and their dignity, and that is harmful to physical and mental development. For instance:
	Combining school with long and intense hours of work;
	Work that causes a child to leave school prematurely;
	Work that prevents a child from attending school.

The age of the child must also be considered. ILO Convention No. 138 concerning Minimum Age for Admission to Employment specifies that minimum age for work should not be below the age for finishing compulsory schooling, which is generally 15.
